[1] India - Bihar
Date: 27 Dec 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hindustan Times [edited]
<http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/181_1880057,000600030006.htm>

Polio cases rise to 50 this year [2006] in Bihar
-----------------------------------------------
Despite umpteen [many] rounds of the pulse polio immunization program
in the state, 2 fresh cases of poliomyelitis were reported in Bihar
last week. With this, the total number of children afflicted with the
debilitating disease in the State rose to 50 this year [2006]. The
figure in 2005 was 30.
The 2 new cases were detected in East Champaran and Sitamarhi. What
has worried doctors is that both the kids had been administered polio
drops more than 4 times. Other children who were afflicted with the
disease this year [2006] had also been immunized against the virus.
When contacted, state immunization officer Dr. Gopal Krishna
confirmed the development and said that medical officers of the
districts concerned were trying to find out the causes that led to
the new cases. "Maybe the immunity level of the children was low," he added.
8 rounds of the PPI program had been carried out in the current year
[2006]. With 50 cases of poliomyelitis, Bihar ranks next to Uttar
Pradesh, where 501 patients were detected this year [2006] alone.
The other cases were reported from Haryana (16), Uttaranchal (13),
Punjab (7), Maharashtra (5), Gujarat (3), Madhya Pradesh (3), Assam
(2) and one each reported from Chandigarh, Himachal Pradesh, West
Bengal & Jharkhand.
[Byline: Binod Dubey]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to the most recent information on the polio eradication
website, there have been 597 cases of polio confirmed in India as of
19 Dec 2006, as compared with 57 cases reported during the same
period in 2005 (see
<http://www.polioeradication.org/casecount.asp>).
From the above newswire, the information on the vaccination
histories of the newest cases as having had 4 or more prior doses of
polio vaccine raises concerns as to possible reasons for the vaccine
failures. The most disconcerting of the possible explanations is that
there may have been a break in the cold chain, leading to a loss of
potency of the vaccine administered. The oral polio vaccine (OPV),
which is used in the vaccination activities in most countries in the
world, is made of attenuated live polioviruses (types 1, 2 and 3).
This vaccine is heat labile so that storage at ambient temperatures
can lead to a loss of potency, as the vaccine viruses die when kept
at temperatures above 8 C for prolonged periods. Vaccines are to be
stored and transported at temperatures lower than 8 C at all times
through a logistical system referred to as the cold chain. A break in
the cold chain could result in the administration of many doses of
vaccine that have lost their potency. Other possible reasons for
vaccine failure in a child could be concurrent infection with other
enteroviruses at the time of receipt of the vaccine, so that
intestinal receptor sites are unavailable to the vaccine virus. This
latter reason is more of a challenge to deal with, as many of these
children are not brought for routine vaccination activities and are
only reached during specified times when there are vaccination
campaign activities.
More information on the investigations into the epidemiology of these
cases in India would be appreciated.
A good map of India can be found at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/india_pol01.jpg>,
and to see districts within Bihar, see
<http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/bihar/bihar-district.htm>.
- Mod.MPP]
