[2] Bangladesh - Sylhet
Date: 27 Dec 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Daily India [edited]
<http://www.dailyindia.com/show/96254.php/Bangladesh-to-immunize-24-million-children-against-polio>

Bangladesh to immunize 24 million children against polio
-----------------------------------------------
Bangladesh is immunizing 24 million children today [23 Dec 2006] in a
bid to eradicate polio from the country.
It is the 6th national immunization day in Bangladesh. It was
declared polio-free in the year 2000 by the World Health
Organization, but 17 cases have been reported recently. To stamp out
this incurable disease, Bangladesh is fighting hard to become a
polio-free nation again.
A 2-year-old boy in a village near Sylhet, 350 km northeast of the
capital, Dhaka, was found to have the virus.
One of the medical officers in Sylhet said that the Dhaka-based
National Polio Laboratory has confirmed the case.
This case was reported in March this year [2006], triggering national
alarm and the introduction of a wide scale vaccination program.
The Bangladesh government started immunizing children under 5 years
against polio by launching a nationwide drive. It has appointed 60
medical experts to keep watch and take appropriate steps to monitor
and curb the disease. These officers are the representatives of
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) and World Health Organization (WHO).
Medical officials in Bangladesh believe that the latest polio
epidemic may have originated from India, which reported 583 polio
cases in 2006.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[In the most recent available polio eradication website update (19 Dec 2006
<http://www.polioeradication.org/casecount.asp#details>),
there is mention that: "Pre-notification of 2 new cases (type 1) was
received from Sylhet province. The cases had onset of paralysis on 29
Oct [2006] and 4 Nov [2006]. Bangladesh's most recent NIDs [National
Immunization Days] were conducted on 25 Nov [2006]. The next NIDs
will be launched on 23 Dec [2006]."
In an earlier report, genetic studies on earlier poliovirus isolates
in Bangladesh showed they were related to viruses circulating in
western Uttar Pradesh, India (see Poliomyelitis - Worldwide (04):
Bangladesh 20060316.0822 & Poliomyelitis - worldwide (04):
Bangladesh, correction 20060321.0873), hence, the statement in the
above newswire that the original reintroduction of polio into
Bangladesh was related to continued poliovirus circulation in
neighboring India.
The most recent update on numbers of reported cases of polio in
Bangladesh is 15 cases for 2006, as compared with no cases reported
in 2005 <http://www.polioeradication.org/casecount.asp>.
The 2 additional cases mentioned in the "pre-notification report"
bring the total reported cases this year (2006) to 17. The obvious
concern is that local transmission of the wild poliovirus will
continue now that Bangladesh has been re-seeded with wild poliovirus.
Good maps of Bangladesh can be found at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/banglade.pdf> and
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/bangladesh_pol96.jpg>.
- Mod.MPP]
